Part 3:<p>&quot;Wait a tic... Where&#x27;s the Makefile? I&#x27;ve got just about as much chance of finding it as the FBI does of finding Jimmy Hoffa. Am I just supposed to imagine it into existence?&quot;<p>I think the point is that the make command can use implicit rules even if there is no Makefile. It knows how to compile C source files. (This could be confusing if you know about &quot;make&quot; but don&#x27;t know about implicit rules.) For example:<p><pre><code>    $ ls
    hello.c
    $ cat hello.c
    #include <stdio.h>
    int main(void) {
        puts(&quot;hello&quot;);
        return 0;
    }
    $ make hello
    cc     hello.c   -o hello
    $ ./hello
    hello
    $
</code></pre>
Later: &quot;So, I&#x27;m just supposed to poke in some code, go to my terminal, type this magic &#x27;make&#x27; word, and expect a built and working program, right?&quot;<p>Yes, that&#x27;s exactly what you&#x27;re supposed to do. Try it, it should work.<p>Part 10 mentions strncpy() as a safer strcpy().  It isn&#x27;t. <a href="http://the-flat-trantor-society.blogspot.com/2012/03/no-strncpy-is-not-safer-strcpy.html" rel="nofollow">http://the-flat-trantor-society.blogspot.com/2012/03/no-strn...</a><p>(Disclaimer: I haven&#x27;t read Zed Shaw&#x27;s book, and I don&#x27;t intend to.)
